caption: I wish it was open
Pretty authentic Chicago place. Also my favorite place to get Pierogis downtown.
Delicious! Fast, friendly service.

I really wish the guy behind the counter had been actually nice. He was very abrupt. I did not know I was required to order online first. I do NOT like that I cannot mix and match pierogi fillings. I was forced to order 9 of the same type. I can go to the store and buy 12 pierogis of the same type if that's what I wanted. The appeal of having so many different types would be if you could pick and choose which ones you want. He ended the transaction by bringing my meal to the door and said "thank you" okay. At least you ended it somewhat congenially. But if it hadn't been for my friend with me, I would have skipped the place altogether for how I was yelled at when I arrived.  Look I feel bad that someone bust the glass in your door. And yes, this pandemic is tweaking everyone out, but your livelihood depends on repeat customers. And you lost me with your gruff attitude. The pierogis were good though. But that's not what it's all about it anymore. Good food with a side order of verbal abuse is not something I feel like paying for. I hope everyone else has a better experience. But, the woman that came to the door was asking him about mixing and matching pierogis too and she got frustrated with him, threw up her hands and left, muttering "it's just not worth it." So maybe this is just the norm.

You cannot judge a book by its cover. The awning looks old, the lighting makes it feel like an old deli, but the food is on point. I wish the pierogi's had a little bit more oil/moisture/flavor, but I thoroughly enjoyed my time here. Keep small businesses going!!
Small out of the way spot,  but everything is delish

very authentic

We were in town for wedding (from TX) and figured we could get some home made pierogi's, these reminded me of the ones by polish grandma use to make! YUMMY! so glad we found this place! the only thing they didn't have was extra melted butter, but there were still outstanding! I had the potato and cheese ones and my daughter had the fruit filled, they were delicious! i would go back again the next time I come to Chicago!

Disappointed. I was born in Poland and really hoped to try Polish cuisine here in Chicago. Travelled all the way up from Miami to be closer to home flavors... Nope.. Missed approach. I was served pre-cooked, frozen pierogi that I can buy myself in a supermarket half-price! What a shame. Borscht was decent though.
Try the Polish sausage! It is a quality that is hard to come by in America. Reminds me of home in the best possible way.

Quick food stop with excellent options. We especially liked the mushroom and potato cheddar, and I was happy with the borscht too! I'm Ukrainian so the Polish food was a bit different than I'm used to (the borscht is not vegetarian), but it was a great experience overall.

Get the potatoes and cheese pierogi's and a sausage or two.  They were just amazing and tasted just like the ones I had. In Poland and Ukraine last summer.
Really good food. Cute little place.

I wouldn’t call it heaven. It wasn’t bad but it wasn’t delicious as well. As a Polish woman I can tell they could be way more tasty but considering the place - they are okay. Just ok - don’t expect anything extra and don’t expect traditional polish cuisine since it’s just not. The filling of pierogis (flavour) is a little bit hard, should be softer (especially the ones with meat, spinach and meat&spinach. As we are here: true polish cuisine do not recognize the meat&spinach filling, it just doesn’t go well together, this combination is not a tasty one. Kraut and mushroom filling is okay, no regrets and no astonishments. The dough of the pierogis is way too thick and hard. Soup (red borsch) gives a feeling as made from the powder or some concentrate. It’s ok but still you won’t be delighted. But it’s served in a big portion! Summing up: for people who don’t know the true polish cuisine it’s a nice place to go, you will eat there a decent meal in a nice price. For people who know polish traditions - better not, you won’t be satisfied. I don’t regret but I wouldn’t go there again.

For the locals I'm sure they know what pierogi are, but for those who don't - you've got to try this place. We went there for two meals in just few days, because it was so good. Fresh pierogi with many variety fillings from meat, mushroom to sweet fruit. They also serve other meals, including stuffed cabbage " golabki". Place is a small room on busy street, different level of fast food done well. You can sit down and eat there ( self service) or take out, you can call in and pick your order to go. On my list to visit every time when will go to Chicago.
St. Peter would be so proud

We're Ukrainian so we know the real thing, and the pierogi here are great especially the potato with cheese and the fruit filled ones. The variaty of other filling is not authentic, still nice to have. But the borscht is not the real thing - it's not made with rich stock, probably just a powered mix. But if you get it opt for the bowl which comes with lots of dumplings - again not the real authentic "little ears" but more like the Asian variety. It makes for a nice beverage.

Simply perfect! We are at the end of our 3 months trip in the US so we really wanted to eat Polish food after so many burgers and stakes. Guess what? This is part of Poland in the US. Pierogi are even better then my mom makes! You must try Kraut and mushrooms, spinach (!) and all of the sweet ones.

The carmelized onions are good and bacon is alright, although the seem like the processed kind you'd find at a salad bar.  First time having pierogies so a little tough reviewing. Also never had sour cream with them but definitely a good combo.  Overall, a decent place to get something quick for under $10!

Was in downtown Chicago this past weekend for two days. We stumbled upon this place while in the hotel looking for polish restaurants near our hotel. Ordered the two polish sausages dinner which was very good and my wife had 6 pierogi's which consisted of 3 potato and cheese which she did not like because they were bland and 3 mushroom pierogi's which she loved. Very friendly staff and a cozy atmosphere.  The only disappointment that I have with this place is the to go order that I placed before leaving Chicago and heading home. With the tip included the total came out to $64.00. Wasn't disappointed on the price that I paid for the food as it was inexpensive while also being located in Chicago. The disappointment was the cabbage rolls as I have had alot better than pierogi heaven. The cabbage rolls were mainly filled with rice and had very little meat in them. The tomato sauce that was on the cabbage rolls was very thin and not alot of sauce were on the rolls. Will definitely take a pass on this place next time were in Chicago looking for polish food.

first time I came here was in 2011 and I'm really glad they are still around as they provide much needed ethnic variety to the mainstream loop options. early on there were mumblings that the pierogis were from alexandra's (a local polish grocer/supplier) but who cares. the menu is simple and delicious with a variety of pierogis and toppings and a couple of great surprises in the stuffed cabbage and the borscht soup.

Had to see what all the hype was about and were glad we did. Kraut and Mushroom, cheese and potato sweet cheese and cheese were all delicious and I highly recommend. Didnt catch the names of who was working today but you two were so sweet, so thank you for being nice to every customer walking in the door. It was so welcoming and next time I come to Chicago I will be back.

We absolutely loved this place.  It's always hard to find good Polish food and Pierogi Heaven didn't disappoint! After walking around aimlessly for about 3 hours we found ourselves knocking on the door to heaven and walking out with 20 pierogi.  Our entire walk home we kept wanting to reach into the box and crush 1 (or 10 of them).  When we got home we ate the entire box in less than 3 minutes.  We will be there again shortly!

The restaurant itself is a no frills kinda place and the food here is great! We ordered the sausage plate which came with two sausages, mashed potatoes, and sauerkraut. The sausages were grilled perfectly. The casing was just slightly crispy which made for a enjoyable texture. The kraut was surprisingly mild and went well with the meal. We also did a sampler of the pierogi which consisted of 3 spinach, 3 spinach and meat, 3 potato and cheddar, and 3 fruit. The spinach, spinach and meat, and the potato cheddar were all great. They were cooked well and contained a good amount of filling. The fruit pierogis had tart cherries inside and were a great finish to the whole meal. We will definately go back and would recommend you try it too!
Thats how I remember best pierogi from Poland. Great job.
Delicious and fast. Definitely recommend if you're nearby.

Good quick lunch place with solid polish food. No frills but worked for me. I liked the meet pierogis but was a tad dry but still tasty. Potato and cheese also good. The sausage was very good.   The staff was very helpful and friendly.

I gave this place a try and here's my thoughts: good pierogi dough, kraut and mushrooms ok, ruskie meh, meat and spinach ok but need some spices. My wife had kraut and potato and cheddar. Potato and cheddar were ok, kraut were awful (old kraut or something). Overall far from classic polish pierogies.

Quiet, little place with amazing food and staff! Ordering was easy and service was fast. The food was really good and each flavor delivered what it promised. The staff is absolutely amazing. The  guy who helped us was super friendly and made me want to come back. Definitely coming back!
Great food, friendly service. Not a date-night place, but awesome for a quick, authentic bite.
delicious-ness on a plate.

This is a stellar little place to grab some super tasty food. Low key and casual, with awesome and friendly staff. The wife and I felt really at home, and not only are their pierogis pretty tasty, but their sauerkraut and sausage is also really good. Give this place a go.
Reasonably priced Polish comfort food, served up quickly
You could easily miss this place but it's worth a quick stop I'd say. I had never had pierogis before but really enjoyed them!
The specials are amazing.. Especially the polish sausage one!
Small restaurant, nothing fancy, but the pierogis are reallllly good. The Polish sausages are also amazing. Try a bit of everything, you won't be disappointed. (Also, no public restroom here).

GO HERE!  Literally stop what you're doing, get off your phone, stop trolling Google, and get. to. this. restaurant.  Because when you cross the threshold you're not just getting dinner, you're leaving Chicago and entering Poland. I've eaten pierogis in/from Poland a handful of times, and these are the first pierogis since returning to the States that are the real deal.  The owner is friendly and even let me break out some of my rusty Polish during our visit. 6 pierogis is probably plenty for one person, but I didn't die after eating 9. Personal favorites are the meat and spinach, but they're all good. Get it with the bacon, onino and sour cream - that's the traditional way. Oh, and they take to-go orders, too!  Why are you still reading??  GO HERE!!!

Delicious, authentic polish food right in the loop.  Small space for seating (5 tables and a counter), so can get packed at the peak of lunch, but well worth it.
Very small polish place in the heart of the city. The food was nice but the staff need to be a bit more friendly. Overall an okay experience.

I was really excited for Polish food here in Chicago, so I am crushed at the experience here. I ordered several varieties, asked for butter onion and sour cream, only to be told that they have no butter, they only boil. Ok. First strike.  I asked that the sweet ones not have onions ( sweet cheese and onion is not a good combo for me) nope. All mixed up. Second strike. I specifically asked for no bacon. And yet, I spent the entireity of the meal picking the bacon off of my plate. And the people working there could not be less interested in customer service. Skip this place.

I was really excited about this place until I asked the guy if he could show me how big one of the pierogis is and he pulled it out of a bag in the freezer.  If I wanted frozen/boiled periogi I could buy them at the grocery store and make them myself.  With that said, the "toppings" offered at PH made them more tasty: chopped sauteed onion and real bacon bits (sour cream as well if desired).
